<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-125-252 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 890 486</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  June 24 1991 v8 n25 p54(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM puts Windows pizzazz into 3270 terminal emulator. (IBMPersonal Communications/3270) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Musich, Paula.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   Personal Communications/3270 2.0 (Computer terminal emulator)(Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Terminal emulationUtility programsSoftware packages.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Paula MusichandM;In a bid to remain competitive in the 3270 terminal-emulation softwaremarket, IBM recently added Windows 3.0 support to a new version of itsPersonal Communications/3270 software.andM;IBM Personal Communications/3270 version 2.0, a distributed function terminal(DFT) emulator that supports multiple host sessions, incorporates the IBMWindows Connection to usher in the graphical capabilities of Windows 3.0.andP;  AsIBM delivers its first 3270 emulator with Windows support, third-partyvendors such as Attachmate Corp. are introducing their second-generationWindows emulation products, industry observers said.andM;IBM's $495 DFT emulator has been bolstered with features that are alsopresent in a new version of the company's single-session control unitterminal mode emulator -- the $345 3270 Emulation Program, Entry Levelversion 2.0.andM;Both offerings, available now directly from IBM, include newnetwork-management features, easier installation procedures and improved 3270display compatibility, according to company officials.andM;IBM, of White Plains, N.Y., can be reached at (800) 426-2468.andO;</TEXT></DOC>